---
// src/pages/manifesto.astro
---

<html lang="it">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Manifesto - Stop Wasting</title>
    <style>
      body {
        background-color: black;
        color: #ff0000; /* Rosso acceso richiesto */
        font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; /* Font serif come nello screenshot */
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        justify-content: center;
        align-items: center;
        min-height: 100vh;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 20px;
        box-sizing: border-box;
      }

      .terminal-container {
        max-width: 900px;
        text-align: center;
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        align-items: center;
      }

      p {
        font-size: 1.6rem; /* Dimensione del testo per riempire bene lo schermo */
        line-height: 1.3;
        text-transform: uppercase; /* Converte automaticamente in maiuscolo */
        margin-bottom: 2rem;
      }

      button {
        background-color: white;
        color: black;
        border: none;
        padding: 4px 12px;
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        font-size: 0.8rem;
        font-weight: bold;
        letter-spacing: 1px;
        cursor: pointer;
        text-transform: uppercase;
      }

      button:hover {
        background-color: #cccccc;
      }

      /* Responsive per dispositivi mobili */
      @media (max-width: 768px) {
        p {
          font-size: 1.1rem;
        }
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="terminal-container">
      <p>
        This new trend of sharing the best quality of products just because in theory they can last longer it’s just bullshit. We sell you DTG printed tshirt, which, for the market, is just the worst kind of printing. Just face to face, who cares? I mean, stuff has to age, we love to see things with cracks, holes, and many more artefacts that only by wearing your clothes you get. It’s starting to get very boring to have a wardrobe with completely new and intact pieces, in a world full of changes, of liquid thoughts, have some point of references, buy stuff that can have the marks of your life on it, that gets old with cracks on the print and can possibly get printed again one day. This our t-shirt single stitch from the 90s, nothing new, history here guys. Stop wasting.
      </p>
      <button onclick="window.history.back()">ACCEPT</button>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>